      • removeIP

        public void removeIP(java.lang.String data)
        The ip will not actually be removed to preserve statistics
        Note that addresses are not translated into InetAddress objects until later, so you can have two names in memory poiting to the same IP address. In that case, only the first match will be used.
        Parameters:
        data - The malicious IP to add in the memory. Can also be a hostname.

      • checkAndAddIPStatIfNecessary

        public void checkAndAddIPStatIfNecessary(java.net.InetAddress addrSource,
                                java.net.InetAddress addrDest,
                                org.jnetpcap.PcapIf currIf)
        Checks if addrSource or addrDest (or both) are in the malicious IP list. If yes, then an entry is made in the statistics. If both IPs are malicious, an entry is made for both.
        Parameters:
        addrSource - The source IP address
        addrDest - The destination IP address
        currIf - The interface this capture was made on. Used to determine the interface's name and IP, which will be used to store the statistics if necessary.

      • checkAndAddPayloadStatIfNecessary

                                     org.jnetpcap.PcapIf currIf)
        Checks the payload string for malicious string patterns and adds them to the statistics if necessary.
        Parameters:
        string - The payload string to check for malicious string patterns
        currIf - The interface this capture was made on. Used to determine the interface's name and IP, which will be used to store the statistics if necessary.
